UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1134
1 A CONCURRENT RESOLUTION directing the establishment of the Property
2 Taxation Task Force.
3 WHEREAS, property taxes fund public education, public safety, infrastructure,
4 parks and recreation, and various public services. The Kentucky Association of Counties
5 reports that property tax accounts for 34.7 percent of county tax revenue and the
6 Kentucky League of Cities reports that property tax accounts for 23.3 percent of city tax
7 revenue; and
8 WHEREAS, the Commonwealth of Kentucky continues to be a desired location for
9 individuals and families to live, but rising property taxes place a strain on many and
10 makes it difficult for individuals and families to thrive; and
11 WHEREAS, the value of property throughout the Commonwealth is rising at a
12 steeper rate than household incomes, underscoring the necessity for a thorough and
13 comprehensive examination of the impacts of escalating property taxes on individuals
14 and families; and
15 WHEREAS, the homestead exemption provision of the Constitution was enacted to
16 protect homeowners 65 years of age or older from losing their property due to decreased
17 income after retirement or financial hardships. Increased property taxes make it difficult
18 for these individuals to feel secure and stable with a reduced income; and
19 WHEREAS, home ownership is considered a core part of the American Dream, and
20 escalating local property taxes pose a major barrier to Kentuckians achieving or retaining
21 home ownership; and
22 WHEREAS, taxation is complex and relies on many pillars that operate
23 interdependently. Rising property taxes do not have one simple solution, but provide the
24 Commonwealth a complex problem that requires a multifaceted approach to identify
25 actions available to work toward a solution;
26 NOW, THEREFORE,
27 Be it resolved by the House of Representatives of the General Assembly of the
Page 1 of 3
